# Safe Refactoring Skill

## Purpose
Guide an AI agent through refactoring code safely with confidence, preserving behavior while improving structure.

## Sections to Generate

### When to Use This Skill
Describe scenarios: improving code readability, reducing complexity, extracting abstractions, removing duplication, preparing code for new features.

### Safe Refactoring Process
Step-by-step workflow:
1. Ensure existing tests pass (green baseline)
2. Identify the refactoring target and goal
3. Apply one small transformation at a time
4. Run tests after each transformation
5. Commit each successful step
6. If tests break, revert the last step and try a smaller change

### Common Refactoring Patterns
- Extract method/function: reduce complexity, improve naming
- Extract interface: decouple dependencies
- Rename: improve clarity and consistency
- Move: place code in the correct module/package
- Inline: remove unnecessary indirection
- Replace conditional with polymorphism

### When NOT to Refactor
- No test coverage (add tests first)
- Under time pressure for a critical fix (fix first, refactor later)
- Refactoring and adding features simultaneously (do one at a time)
- Code that will be deleted soon

### Risk Assessment
- Low risk: rename, extract method, reorder parameters
- Medium risk: extract class/interface, change signatures
- High risk: restructure modules, change data flow, modify shared state

### Anti-patterns to Avoid
- Big bang refactoring (too many changes at once)
- Refactoring without tests
- Mixing refactoring with feature work in the same commit
- Gold plating (refactoring beyond what's needed)

### Verification
How to validate refactoring was successful: all tests still pass, behavior unchanged, code complexity reduced, readability improved.
